# Index

## Files
- `omo-agentic-arms-race.md` — Competitive analysis of Oh My OpenCode's multi-model agent orchestration vs Origami's formal graph framework. Concept mapping, gaps, advantages, actionable takeaways.
- `crewai-crews-and-flows.md` — Competitive analysis of CrewAI (44.6k stars, market leader). Crews+Flows duality vs Origami's unified graph. Agent-in-YAML, cross-walk memory, hierarchical delegation gaps.
- `ansible-collections.md` — Ansible Collections as a distribution model for agentic frameworks. Package format, FQCNs, Galaxy registry mapped to Origami. Implementation extracted to `origami-collections` + `origami-lsp`.
- `visual-editor-landscape.md` — Visual editor business model analysis: Excalidraw (SaaS), Mermaid (SaaS), Ansible Automation Controller (open-core). Recommends Ansible open-core model for Origami. Implementation extracted to `visual-editor`.
- `langgraph-graph-duality.md` — Competitive analysis of LangGraph (25.1k stars, Pregel-inspired). State-centric vs walker-centric graph philosophy. Durable execution, HITL, subgraph, memory gaps. Infrastructure vs intelligence ceiling thesis.
- `cloud-native-circuit-tools.md` — CNCF cloud-native ecosystem analysis: Argo Workflows (infrastructure), Tekton (adapter), KEDA (infrastructure), Falco (adapter), CloudEvents (adapter). Integration matrix, competitive positioning, 11 extracted tasks.
- `electronic-circuit-theory.md` — Cross-domain pattern study mapping electronic circuit theory (ADC/DAC, signal conditioning, impedance matching, Kirchhoff's laws, mixed-signal architecture) onto Origami's circuit primitives. Six transferable patterns, four gaps illuminated, seven actionable takeaways. Worked example: mixed-signal temperature controller (555 timer + ADC + DAC) with 1:1 agentic isomorph (Scheduler + Extractor + Renderer).
- `electronic-symbols-washi-pictograms.md` — Case study mapping IEC 60617/IEEE 315 electronic schematic symbols and circuit diagram conventions onto Washi's visual language. Proposes the Origami Symbol Standard (OSS): three-tier pictogram vocabulary (Node/Edge/Zone/Walker/Processor/Control/Terminal), D/S boundary rendering, semantic zoom levels, Component Palette layout, and EDA-to-Washi feature comparison. Positions Washi as a schematic editor, not a generic graph editor.